<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ911001-0141</DOCNO><DOCID>911001-0141.</DOCID><HL>   LEISURE andamp; ARTS:   Time Off: Diversions and Excursions Oct. 1-14</HL><DATE>10/01/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A18</SO><LP>                                                                                                                                New York                     The Art of Babar                                                                                                       </LP><TEXT>   Almost 150 original drawings created for the classicseries of Babar children's books. Frenchman Jean de Brunhofffirst wrote about an adventurous elephant in 1931 andfollowed with seven additional stories. After his death, sonLaurent continued the series; the majority of the works onview are from his collection.   National Academy of Design: 1083 Fifth Ave. between 89thand 90th streets. Through Nov. 3. (212) 369-4880.                                                                                                                   Masterpieces of the Morgan Library                                                                                                          The library celebrates the completion of its $30 millionexpansion and renovation with this exhibit of more than 275works from the permanent collection, including masterdrawings, medieval and Renaissance manuscripts and rarebooks. The purchase and renovation of the former home of J.Pierpont Morgan's son, J.P. Morgan Jr. (the library'sfounder), doubled the library's space and allowed for thecreation of new galleries devoted entirely to objects fromthe permanent collection as well as an education center. Aglass-enclosed landscaped garden connects the brownstone tothe library's original building, which was built in 1906 byMcKim, Mead andamp; White to house J. Pierpont Morgan's privatecollections.   Pierpont Morgan Library: 29 East 36th St. at MadisonAvenue. Through Jan. 5. (212) 685-0008.                                                                                                                              San Francisco                   Beyond the Java Sea:             Art of Indonesia's Outer Islands                                                                                                          More than 200 works crafted by peoples of Indonesia's13,000-plus outer islands. Dating from the 19th and early20th centuries, they include elaborate beadwork, sculptures,textiles and gold jewelry.   M.H. de Young Memorial Museum: Golden Gate Park. ThroughJan. 5. (415) 863-3330.                                                                                                                                                                                                                                       New York                   Benson andamp; Hedges Blues                                                                                                          This blues festival premiered in Houston, traveled to LosAngeles, Dallas and Atlanta and now comes to New York with anall-star lineup. The three headline concerts feature B.B.King, John Mayall and the Bluesbrakers, Johnnie Taylor, andRoomful of Blues (Oct. 18); Al Green, Bobby &quot;Blue&quot; Bland andthe Staple Singers (Oct. 19); and blues guitarists John LeeHooker, Buddy Guy and John Campbell (Oct. 20).   Beacon Theater: 2124 Broadway at 74th Street. Oct. 11-20.(212) 307-7171.                                                                                                                              Philadelphia                      Festival Mythos                                                                                                          A month of dance, theater, exhibitions, films, lectures,symposiums and special programs exploring the way artistshave interpreted and incorporated myths of different culturesinto their work. Sponsored by the University of the Arts andthe Native Land Foundation, the festival includes performanceevents such as: the American premiere of &quot;Achilles,&quot; directedand designed in the Kabuki style by Shozo Sato and performedby the People's Light and Theater Company (Oct. 4-20); andworld premieres of commissioned works by Elizabeth Swados(Oct. 4 and 5) and Garth Fagan (Oct. 26).   Various venues, through Oct. 31. (215) 875-LIST.                                                                                                                                  MUSIC                                                                                                                                New York                    Metropolitan Opera                                                                                                          Puccini's &quot;La Fanciulla del West&quot; (&quot;Girl of the GoldenWest&quot;) is the Met's first new production this season, acharmingly corny opera about a Bible-reading, pistol-totingsaloon keeper. Cast includes Barbara Daniels as Minnie,Placido Domingo as the outlaw and Sherrill Milnes as thesheriff. Leonard Slatkin conducts.   Metropolitan Opera House, Lincoln Center: 65th andBroadway. Oct. 10, 14, 18, 23, 26 and 29. (212) 362-6000.                                                                                                                           New York City Opera                                                                                                          Christopher Keene conducts Bernd Alois Zimmermann's 1960opera &quot;Die Soldaten,&quot; based on an 18th-century story aboutthe destruction of a merchant's daughter by a callous armyofficer. Rhoda Levine is the director; John Conklin is thedesigner.   New York State Theater, Lincoln Center: 65th and Broadway.Oct. 8, 12, 17, 23 and Nov. 1.</TEXT></DOC>